SIMPLE: remit
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Remit
<hw>Re*mit"</hw> <pr>(r?-m?t")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Remitted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Remitting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>remittere</ets>,
<ets>remissum</ets>, to send back, to slacken, relax; pref.
<ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>mittere</ets> to send. See <er>Mission</er>,
and cf. <er>Remise</er>, <er>Remiss</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
send back; to give up; to surrender; to resign.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the case the law <qex>remits</qex> him to his ancient and more
certain right.</q> <rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In grevious and inhuman crimes, offenders should be
<qex>remitted</qex> to their prince.</q>
<rj><qau>Hayward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The prisoner was <qex>remitted</qex> to the guard.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To restore.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The archbishop was . . . <qex>remitted</qex> to his liberty.</q>
<rj><qau>Hayward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Com.)</fld> <def>To transmit or send, esp. to a
distance, as money in payment of a demand, account, draft, etc.; <as>as,
he <ex>remitted</ex> the amount by mail</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To send off or away; hence: <sd>(a)</sd> To refer or
direct (one) for information, guidance, help, etc.
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Remitting</xex> them . . . to the works of Galen.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Sir T. Elyot.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> To submit, refer, or leave
(something) for judgment or decision.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Whether the counsel
be good I <xex>remit</xex> it to the wise readers.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir T.
Elyot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To relax in intensity; to make less violent; to
abate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So willingly doth God <qex>remit</qex> his ire.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To forgive; to pardon; to remove.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose soever sins ye <qex>remit</qex>, they are
<qex>remitted</qex> unto them.</q> <rj><qau>John xx. 23.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To refrain from exacting or enforcing; <as>as, to
<ex>remit</ex> the performance of an obligation</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
sovereign was undoubtedly competent to <xex>remit</xex>
penalties.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To relax; release; abate; relinguish; forgive;
pardon; absolve.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Remit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Remit
<hw>Re*mit"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To abate in force or
in violence; to grow less intense; to become moderated; to abate; to
relax; <as>as, a fever <ex>remits</ex>; the severity of the weather
<ex>remits</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To send money, as in payment.</def>
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Remitment</ent>⟦br⟧
